+# Element Web Client
+
+Element Web is the browser client for the private Synapse homeserver. It is
+served at `https://element.hl.maier.wtf` on a domain separate from
+`matrix.hl.maier.wtf`, as recommended by Element's upstream security guidance.
+Public TLS terminates at the established frontproxy; the container serves plain
+HTTP on port 8080 only inside `frontproxy_default` and publishes no host port.
+
+The static configuration fixes the homeserver to
+`https://matrix.hl.maier.wtf`. Custom homeserver URLs, guests, the registration
+UI, public room/space creation, identity-server features, integrations, widgets,
+VoIP, and Element Call are disabled. PostHog, Sentry, rageshake, and other
+analytics/telemetry endpoints are not configured. The file contains no account,
+credential, token, or other secret.
+
+## Image and upstream contract
+
+- Image: Element Web `v1.12.23`, published as `vectorim/element-web`.
+- Immutable OCI index: `sha256:2a65f32acc6fd7163523d1c4b5174de354b5ceb085898b15898f4d8ea01a8e3d`.
+- The Docker Hub registry manifest for that index contains the Pi-compatible
+  `linux/arm64` child manifest
+  `sha256:f3cf1b621a985e1eebbc1ee8a6bd9dae430cf415a17384c482d3fa753c90f232`.
+- Upstream's [installation documentation](https://github.com/element-hq/element-web/blob/v1.12.23/docs/install.md#docker)
+  defines `/app/config.json` as the custom static-config mount and
+  `ELEMENT_WEB_PORT` as the internal HTTP listener override. The upstream image
+  runs as its unprivileged `nginx` user and supplies a healthcheck against
+  `/config.json` on that port.
+- The configuration keys follow upstream's
+  [configuration reference](https://github.com/element-hq/element-web/blob/v1.12.23/docs/config.md):
+  omitted PostHog settings disable analytics, while integration-manager URLs set
+  to `null` disable integrations.
+
+Recheck the immutable index and its ARM64 child before a future image update:
+
+```bash
+docker buildx imagetools inspect \
+  docker.io/vectorim/element-web@sha256:2a65f32acc6fd7163523d1c4b5174de354b5ceb085898b15898f4d8ea01a8e3d
+```
+
+## Prerequisites
+
+Before deployment, the operator must confirm all of the following:
+
+1. The reviewed PR is merged and the deployment checkout is fast-forwarded to
+   that exact merge commit.
+2. Synapse is healthy at `https://matrix.hl.maier.wtf`, private accounts already
+   exist, and public registration remains disabled server-side.
+3. `frontproxy_default` exists and the frontproxy plus ACME companion are
+   healthy.
+4. DNS for `element.hl.maier.wtf` points through the established public proxy.
+   DNS and certificate changes are separate operator actions, not performed by
+   this repository change.
+5. Port 8080 is not published by another Element container; no direct host port
+   is required.
+
+## Manual post-merge deployment
+
+Deployment is deliberately manual. On the Pi, from the clean Architecture
+checkout at the recorded merged commit, the authorized operator runs:
+
+```bash
+git pull --ff-only origin main
+git status --short
+bash pi/tests/test_element_compose.sh
+docker compose -f pi/compose/element.yml config
+docker compose -f pi/compose/element.yml pull
+docker compose -f pi/compose/element.yml up -d
+docker compose -f pi/compose/element.yml ps
+```
+
+Do not deploy from a feature branch. Record the merged commit, OCI index and
+ARM64 child digest, operator, timestamp, container health, certificate result,
+and previous known-good image digest. The Compose file mounts only the reviewed
+static config read-only; it creates no Matrix account and enables no public
+registration.
+
+## Post-deployment smoke test
+
+1. Verify the proxy-facing HTTPS page and certificate:
+
+   ```bash
+   curl --fail --silent --show-error --head https://element.hl.maier.wtf/
+   openssl s_client -connect element.hl.maier.wtf:443 \
+     -servername element.hl.maier.wtf -verify_hostname element.hl.maier.wtf \
+     -verify_return_error </dev/null
+   ```
+
+   Expected: Element returns HTTP 200 through HTTPS and OpenSSL reports
+   `Verify return code: 0 (ok)`.
+
+2. Verify client discovery and the configured homeserver:
+
+   ```bash
+   curl --fail --silent --show-error \
+     https://matrix.hl.maier.wtf/.well-known/matrix/client
+   curl --fail --silent --show-error \
+     https://element.hl.maier.wtf/config.json
+   ```
+
+   Expected: discovery and Element config both identify only
+   `https://matrix.hl.maier.wtf`; Element offers no editable homeserver URL,
+   guest access, or public-registration path.
+
+3. In a private browser window, open `https://element.hl.maier.wtf`, sign in
+   with an existing private account, open an existing private room, send a test
+   message, and sign out. Do not create an account or enable registration.
+
+   Expected: login succeeds against `matrix.hl.maier.wtf`, the message syncs,
+   and no integration manager or analytics consent prompt appears.
+
+4. Confirm there is no host-port binding:
+
+   ```bash
+   container_id="$(docker compose -f pi/compose/element.yml ps -q element)"
+   test -n "$container_id"
+   test "$(docker inspect --format '{{json .HostConfig.PortBindings}}' "$container_id")" = "null"
+   ```
+
+## Rollback
+
+If health, HTTPS, discovery, or private login fails:
+
+1. Save container and proxy/ACME logs without credentials or authorization
+   headers, then stop this stack with
+   `docker compose -f pi/compose/element.yml down`.
+2. Check out the recorded previous known-good merged commit (or restore its
+   digest and config through a reviewed revert) and run `config`, `pull`, and
+   `up -d` for that version. Never replace the digest with `latest`.
+3. Repeat the HTTPS, discovery, no-host-port, and private-login smoke tests.
+4. If no known-good Element deployment exists, leave Element stopped; Synapse
+   remains independently available. Record the rollback commit/digest,
+   operator, time, reason, and verification results.
