+# Matrix Discovery and Federation Mode
+
+The files under `pi/synapse/well-known/` define response examples only. They are
+not mounted by Compose, served by Synapse, copied to a web root, or published by
+this repository state.
+
+## Private Mode
+
+Private mode is the current contract:
+
+- `pi/synapse/synapse.yaml.example` exposes only the `client` listener resource;
+  it does not expose the `federation` resource.
+- `allow_public_rooms_over_federation` is `false`.
+- `serve_server_wellknown` is absent and therefore remains at its `false`
+  default.
+- Compose does not mount or publish the staged well-known examples.
+- The client response points to the public HTTPS homeserver, while the server
+  response remains staged for a future federation decision.
+
+This blocks inbound public federation at the Synapse HTTP listener. It is not a
+network-egress firewall policy; remote-room or federation activation requires a
+separate reviewed change.
+
+Any published client discovery response must include:
+
+```text
+Content-Type: application/json
+Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *
+```
+
+The wildcard origin is required because Matrix clients discover a homeserver
+from origins other than the homeserver itself. Discovery responses contain no
+credentials and must not enable credentialed CORS.
+
+## External Private-Mode Checks
+
+Run these only after an operator has deployed the Matrix endpoint. They do not
+publish files or alter the service.
+
+1. Confirm client discovery, including its CORS header if it has been enabled:
+
+   ```bash
+   curl --fail --silent --show-error --dump-header - \
+     -H 'Origin: https://app.element.io' \
+     https://matrix.hl.maier.wtf/.well-known/matrix/client
+   ```
+
+   Expected: JSON matching `client.json.example`, `Content-Type` containing
+   `application/json`, and `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *`.
+
+2. Confirm that the server discovery document is not published in private mode:
+
+   ```bash
+   test "$(curl --silent --output /dev/null --write-out '%{http_code}' \
+     https://matrix.hl.maier.wtf/.well-known/matrix/server)" = "404"
+   ```
+
+3. Confirm that the federation API is denied:
+
+   ```bash
+   test "$(curl --silent --output /dev/null --write-out '%{http_code}' \
+     https://matrix.hl.maier.wtf/_matrix/federation/v1/version)" = "404"
+   ```
+
+## Activation
+
+Federation activation is reversible but must be a separate reviewed and
+operator-approved change:
+
+1. Record the deployed commit and back up the active Synapse configuration.
+2. Add `federation` beside `client` in the Synapse listener resource names.
+3. Publish `server.json.example` as `/.well-known/matrix/server` with the headers
+   from `headers.example`; publish `client.json.example` independently if client
+   discovery is also required.
+4. Validate the rendered configuration and run the repository test suite.
+5. Deploy through the normal Git workflow, then verify HTTPS, client discovery,
+   federation discovery, and `/_matrix/federation/v1/version` externally.
+6. Record the commit, operator, time, certificate result, and federation test.
+
+## Rollback
+
+1. Remove the published server discovery response first.
+2. Restore the listener resource names to only `client` and redeploy the last
+   reviewed private-mode configuration.
+3. Remove client discovery too if the whole discovery change is being reverted.
+4. Repeat the private-mode checks above and require both server discovery and
+   the federation API to return HTTP 404.
+5. Record the rollback commit, operator, time, and verification results.
