+++ b/docs/matrix/identity-and-access.md
@@ -0,0 +1,203 @@
+# Matrix identity, service-account, and role model
+
+This document defines the identity and access model for the Homelab Matrix
+federation. It covers every identity that interacts with the Matrix homeserver
+(Synapse) and its administrative surface. It is a declarative policy and
+operator runbook only: no account, token, credential, service, or deployment
+change is created by this repository document.
+
+## Scope
+
+The model applies to all Synapse runtime identities including room membership,
+the Admin API, the complement OIDC identity provider (Keycloak), and any bridge
+or gateway component that presents as a Matrix user.
+
+Only Operator is provisioned via the OIDC provider. Break-glass admin is a
+separately pre-provisioned, non-OIDC emergency identity. System identities
+(Lydia, Slarti, Vekling, gateway) are service accounts with Synapse access
+tokens. Each token authenticates its user; room membership and restrictive
+power levels constrain what that user may do.
+No identity in the service-account category is granted server-admin privileges.
+
+## Identity table
+
+| Identity | Authentication | Room scope | Token lifecycle | Revocation owner |
+|---|---|---|---|---|
+| Operator | OIDC via Keycloak (homelab realm) | Full server admin; all rooms | SSO session; no long-lived token | Keycloak admin deletes/expires user |
+| Break-glass admin | Non-OIDC emergency admin identity; offline credential/recovery material outside Git | Server admin; all rooms | Pre-provisioned identity; offline credential/recovery material used during incidents; tested periodically | Operator activates credential from offline storage; tested periodically |
+| Lydia | Service account; Synapse access token | `#homelab`, `#alerts`, `#admin` (escalation) | Token issued per deployment; rotated every 90 days | Operator rotates token; Synapse admin deletes token |
+| Slarti | Service account; Synapse access token | `#homelab`, `#backlog`, `#ops` | Token issued per session; rotated every 90 days | Operator rotates token; Synapse admin deletes token |
+| Vekling | Service account; separate non-admin Synapse user | Task-specific rooms via membership policy; no cross-task access | Ephemeral: created per task, revoked after completion | Automation (Lydia) revokes token via Admin API on task end; Operator escalates |
+| Gateway (bridges) | Service account; Synapse appservice registration | Bridge rooms via AS namespace regex; no server-admin user | Token provisioned with bridge deployment; rotated every 90 days | Operator rotates; Synapse admin deletes appservice registration |
+
+### Human accounts
+
+- **Operator** — the human administrator (Michael). Authenticates via OIDC
+  (Keycloak, `homelab` realm). Has full server-admin access through Synapse's
+  Admin API and room membership. No long-lived Synapse token is stored outside
+  the SSO session.
+- **Break-glass admin** — a separately pre-provisioned, non-OIDC emergency admin
+  identity. Used only when Keycloak OIDC is unreachable. Offline credential or
+  recovery material is held outside Git and tested periodically. The exact
+  account creation, bootstrap, and configuration mechanism is separately
+  reviewed and out of scope for this document.
+
+### Service accounts
+
+- **Lydia** — the execution-plane agent. Authenticates via a Synapse access
+  token. Room membership restricts the identity to operational rooms. Token is
+  set at deployment time and rotated on a 90-day schedule.
+- **Slarti** — the control-plane orchestrator (planning, task graphs).
+  Authenticates via a Synapse access token. Room membership restricts the
+  identity to planning and operations rooms. Token is set at session start and
+  rotated on a 90-day schedule.
+- **Vekling** — ephemeral worker sub-agents. Each Vekling operates as a separate
+  non-admin Synapse user. Task access is enforced via room membership policy
+  and restrictive power levels, not by the token itself. The token is revoked
+  explicitly by Lydia via the Synapse Admin API when the task completes. No
+  Vekling user is ever granted server-admin privileges.
+- **Gateway (bridges)** — application-service bridges (e.g. Signal bridge,
+  Telegram bridge). Each bridge has its own AS registration with an
+  appservice-level token whose namespace is constrained by the AS namespace
+  regex. No gateway has server-admin access.
+
+### Service-account restrictions
+
+**No service account is granted server-admin scope.** This is a hard policy
+constraint. Server-admin access is reserved exclusively for human identities
+(Operator and, in emergencies, the break-glass admin). Service accounts can
+never:
+
+- Call the Synapse Admin API (`/_synapse/admin/`)
+- Modify room state outside their designated rooms
+- Read or write user data, secrets, or tokens for other identities
+- Escalate their own scope
+
+This constraint is enforced at the user level: each service identity is a
+separate non-admin Synapse user. Admin status is a user-level property, not a
+token attribute. Gateway appservice registrations are created without the
+`sender_localpart` belonging to any admin user. The Synapse Admin API must not
+be exposed to or usable by any service identity.
+
+## Authentication summary
+
+| Method | Used by | Notes |
+|---|---|---|
+| OIDC (Keycloak homelab realm) | Operator | SSO; no long-lived credential in repo |
+| Non-OIDC emergency admin identity | Break-glass admin | Offline credential/recovery material outside Git; tested periodically |
+| Synapse access token (non-admin user) | Lydia, Slarti | Rotated 90-day |
+| Synapse access token (non-admin user) | Vekling | Task-specific rooms via membership; revoked via Admin API |
+| Appservice registration | Gateway/bridges | Bridge namespace via AS namespace regex |
+
+## Token lifecycle
+
+All service-account tokens follow the same lifecycle stages:
+
+1. **Provisioning** — a non-admin Synapse access token is generated by the
+   Operator (or by an automated deployment step that the Operator approves) and
+   stored in the deployment runtime secrets store. Never committed to version
+   control.
+2. **Rotation** — every 90 days. The Operator generates a new token, replaces
+   the runtime secret, and restarts the consuming service (or re-authenticates
+   the session). Automation (Lydia) may notify the Operator when rotation is
+   due.
+3. **Revocation** — tokens are deleted via the Synapse Admin API
+   (`DELETE /_synapse/admin/v1/users/{user_id}/token`). For Vekling tokens,
+   revocation is automated: Lydia calls the Admin API endpoint when the task
+   finishes. Gateway tokens are revoked by deleting or disabling the
+   appservice registration.
+
+Do not create an access token, user, or credential as part of a documentation
+change. All tokens are provisioned at runtime by the Operator following this
+policy.
+
+## Revocation procedures
+
+All procedures below are operator-only actions. Do not create accounts, tokens,
+or credentials through this repository.
+
+### Routine revocation (suspected compromise, offboarding, scope change)
+
+1. Identify the affected identity in the table above.
+2. For an OIDC human account: disable or delete the user in Keycloak. The
+   Synapse session expires via back-channel logout.
+3. For a Synapse access token (Lydia, Slarti):
+   ```bash
+   curl -X DELETE "https://matrix.hl.maier.wtf/_synapse/admin/v1/users/@user:hl.maier.wtf/token" \
+     -H "Authorization: Bearer <admin-token>"
+   ```
+4. For a Vekling token: revocation is automated — Lydia calls the same Admin
+   API endpoint when the task finishes. For manual revocation, use the same
+   Admin API endpoint.
+5. For a gateway AS token: delete or disable the appservice registration YAML
+   and restart Synapse.
+
+### Emergency revocation (active compromise)
+
+1. Invalidate all sessions by rotating the Synapse registration secret, or
+   restart Synapse with `enable_registration: false` temporarily.
+2. Follow routine revocation for each affected identity.
+3. Rotate any remaining valid tokens at the next maintenance window.
+
+### Token rotation (routine, every 90 days)
+
+1. Generate a new non-admin Synapse access token:
+   ```bash
+   curl -X POST "https://matrix.hl.maier.wtf/_synapse/admin/v1/users/@user:hl.maier.wtf/token" \
+     -H "Authorization: Bearer <admin-token>" \
+     -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
+     -d '{"valid_until_ms": 7776000000}'  # 90 days in ms
+   ```
+2. Replace the runtime secret in the deployment secrets store.
+3. Restart or re-authenticate the consuming service.
+4. Delete the old token using the routine revocation step.
+5. Confirm the new token works with a `GET /_matrix/client/v3/account/whoami`.
+
+Do not commit the new token value to this or any repository.
+
+## Policy enforcement
+
+### Enforceable controls
+
+The following access-control mechanisms are enforceable at the Synapse and
+deployment level. Service identities are separate non-admin Synapse users;
+their access is constrained by:
+
+- **Room membership** — each service identity is a member only of the rooms it
+  needs. No service identity is invited to rooms outside its operational scope.
+- **Restrictive room power levels** — service identities receive the minimum
+  power level required (typically `power_level: 0`, the default for normal
+  members). They cannot invite other users, change room state, or modify
+  power levels.
+- **Admin API isolation** — the Synapse Admin API (`/_synapse/admin/`) is
+  network-restricted or authentication-gated so that service identities cannot
+  call it. Only Operator and break-glass admin (both human) have access.
+- **Separate accounts and dedicated rooms** — each service identity has its own
+  Synapse user account. Rooms and room aliases are created exclusively for the
+  service's purpose and are not shared with other services.
+- **Token isolation and revocation** — each service identity has its own access
+  token. Tokens are provisioned independently and are revoked individually when
+  the identity is decommissioned or rotated.
+
+### Documentation scope
+
+This document defines the **policy** for Matrix identity and access. It is a
+declarative reference for operators and a specification for the separately
+reviewed deployment and configuration enforcement work. The following are out
+of scope for this document and require separate implementation and review:
+
+- Concrete Synapse configuration files (homeserver.yaml, appservice
+  registrations, room state events)
+- Deployment automation that creates Synapse users, rooms, or tokens
+- Network policies or reverse-proxy rules that restrict Admin API access
+- CI/CD workflows that validate Synapse configuration against this policy
+
+This separation ensures that the identity policy can be reviewed and approved
+independently of the specific deployment mechanism.
+
+## References
+
