+# Keycloak OIDC client for Synapse
+
+This runbook stages a confidential OpenID Connect client for Synapse. It is a
+declarative template and operator procedure only: no realm, client, credential,
+or Synapse runtime configuration is created by this repository change.
+
+## Contract
+
+| Setting | Required value |
+|---|---|
+| Realm | `homelab` (never the `master realm`) |
+| Issuer | `https://auth.hl.maier.wtf/realms/homelab` |
+| Client ID | `synapse` |
+| Client type | Confidential (`publicClient: false`) |
+| Flow | Authorization code only (`standardFlowEnabled: true`) |
+| Redirect URI | `https://matrix.hl.maier.wtf/_synapse/client/oidc/callback` |
+| Back-channel logout | `https://matrix.hl.maier.wtf/_synapse/client/oidc/backchannel_logout` |
+| Requested scopes | `openid profile` |
+| Stable external subject | Keycloak's opaque `sub` claim |
+
+The template explicitly disables the implicit flow, direct access grants,
+service accounts, device authorization, CIBA, authorization services,
+public-client mode, full scope, and all optional client scopes. It grants no web
+origin and accepts no wildcard redirect. The standard `profile` client scope supplies
+`preferred_username`/display-name claims; OIDC supplies `sub`. No role, group,
+email, audience, or custom protocol mapper is added.
+
+Synapse binds the external identity to `sub`, not to a mutable username. A
+username rename can therefore retain the existing external mapping. Do not
+delete and recreate the realm or user as a migration technique: a new Keycloak
+user ID produces a new `sub`.
+
+## Operator procedure
+
+Perform these steps during an approved maintenance window. They are not
+executed as part of this issue.
+
+1. Sign in to the Keycloak Admin Console and inspect the realm selector. Do not
+   import into, add the client to, or otherwise modify the `master realm`.
+2. Confirm that a realm named `homelab` does not already exist. If it does,
+   stop: realm creation/import is not an update mechanism. Export and review
+   the existing realm before planning a separate, non-destructive change.
+3. Choose **Create realm**, select
+   `pi/keycloak/matrix-client-realm-export.example.json`, verify the proposed
+   realm name is exactly `homelab`, then choose **Create**.
+4. In **homelab → Clients → synapse**, verify every value in the contract above.
+   In particular, **Client authentication** must be on, only **Standard flow**
+   may be on, and the redirect URI must be an exact match without `*`.
+5. On the client's **Credentials** tab, generate a fresh client credential.
+   Transfer it through an approved interactive mechanism to the persistent
+   **Host source**
+   `/home/michael/matrix/secrets/oidc_client_secret`. Do not put the value on a
+   command line or paste it into this repository, shell history, issue comments,
+   or logs. **Do not commit** the generated value. The containing directory must
+   be owned by `michael:michael` with mode `0700`; after transfer, set the file
+   ownership to `michael:michael` and mode to `0600`. Verify only its metadata,
+   never its contents:
+
+   ```bash
+   sudo install -d -o michael -g michael -m 0700 /home/michael/matrix/secrets
+   sudo chown michael:michael /home/michael/matrix/secrets/oidc_client_secret
+   sudo chmod 0600 /home/michael/matrix/secrets/oidc_client_secret
+   stat -c '%U:%G %a %n' /home/michael/matrix/secrets/oidc_client_secret
+   ```
+
+   Expected metadata is
+   `michael:michael 600 /home/michael/matrix/secrets/oidc_client_secret`.
+6. This runbook defines a three-stage secret contract. The three paths serve
+   distinct roles and must not be conflated:
+
+   | Stage | Path | Owner:Mode | Purpose |
+   |---|---|---|---|
+   | Host source (stage 1) | `/home/michael/matrix/secrets/oidc_client_secret` | `michael:michael` `0600` | Persistent host-side file (see step 5) |
+   | Compose target (stage 2) | `/run/secrets/synapse_oidc_client_secret` | `michael:michael` `0600` | Docker secret bind mount consumed by a root pre-start step |
+   | Runtime copy (stage 3) | `/run/synapse/oidc_client_secret` | `991:991` `0600` | tmpfs copy readable after Synapse privilege drop |
+
+   The Docker Compose secret bind mount preserves the host file's host-side
+   ownership (`michael:michael` `0600`), making it unreadable after Synapse drops
+   privileges to uid 991 (synapse). A **root pre-start** step must therefore copy
+   the secret from `/run/secrets/synapse_oidc_client_secret` to
+   `/run/synapse/oidc_client_secret` and set ownership to `991:991` and mode
+   `0600` before Synapse starts as the unprivileged user.
+
+   The current Compose file does not declare this secret or grant it to the
+   Synapse service. A separate reviewed Compose/runtime-config change must:
+
+   - declare the host source as a Compose secret;
+   - grant that secret only to the Synapse service and mount it at the
+     container target `/run/secrets/synapse_oidc_client_secret`;
+   - add a root pre-start step to copy the secret to
+     `/run/synapse/oidc_client_secret` with ownership `991:991` and mode
+     `0600`; and
+   - add the provider entry below, pointing `client_secret_path` at the
+     runtime copy, not at the Compose secret mount.
+
+   Do not activate the OIDC provider until that separate change is reviewed,
+   merged, deployed, and `docker compose config` confirms the declaration,
+   service grant, target, and runtime copy permissions. Merely writing a host
+   file under `/run/secrets` does not place it inside the container.
+7. Use the following provider entry in that separate runtime-config change. Do
+   not replace `client_secret_path` with an inline value. The path points to
+   the runtime tmpfs copy (stage 3), not to the Compose secret bind mount
+   (stage 2), because the bind mount preserves host ownership that would be
+   unreadable after Synapse drops privileges.
+
+   ```yaml
+   oidc_providers:
+     - idp_id: keycloak
+       idp_name: Keycloak
+       issuer: "https://auth.hl.maier.wtf/realms/homelab"
+       client_id: "synapse"
+       client_secret_path: "/run/synapse/oidc_client_secret"
+       scopes: ["openid", "profile"]
+       user_mapping_provider:
+         config:
+           subject_claim: "sub"
+           localpart_template: "{{ user.preferred_username }}"
+           display_name_template: "{{ user.name }}"
+       backchannel_logout_enabled: true
+   ```
+
+8. Confirm Synapse has `public_baseurl: "https://matrix.hl.maier.wtf/"`, validate
+   the complete Synapse configuration, and restart Synapse using the approved
+   deployment procedure. A different public base URL changes the callback and
+   must be reviewed before activation.
+9. Before the browser test, verify the non-master discovery document returns
+   issuer `https://auth.hl.maier.wtf/realms/homelab` and that Synapse advertises
+   the Keycloak SSO option in `GET /_matrix/client/v3/login`. Do not print the
+   credential while checking either endpoint.
+
+## Private login/logout smoke test
+
+Use a disposable test user in `homelab`; do not use a Keycloak administrator.
+Run the whole procedure in one new **private browsing window** so existing SSO
+cookies cannot mask a failure.
+
+### Login smoke test
+
+1. Open `https://app.element.io` in the private window and choose **Sign in**.
+2. Set the custom homeserver to `https://matrix.hl.maier.wtf`.
+3. Choose **Continue with Keycloak**. Confirm the browser is sent to
+   `auth.hl.maier.wtf/realms/homelab`, not the master realm.
+4. Sign in as the disposable user and approve the login if prompted.
+5. Confirm Element returns through the exact callback, opens the account, and
+   shows the expected Matrix ID based on `preferred_username`.
+
+Pass: login completes without a local Synapse password, and Synapse associates
+the session with the expected Keycloak user. Fail: redirect mismatch, wrong
+realm, missing SSO option, claim-mapping error, or an unexpected new Matrix
+account for a previously mapped test user.
+
+### Logout smoke test
+
+1. While Element remains signed in, open
+   `https://auth.hl.maier.wtf/realms/homelab/account/` in a second private tab.
+2. Sign out from the Keycloak account console, then return to Element and
+   refresh or trigger a sync.
+3. Confirm the back-channel notification ends the Synapse session and Element
+   requires a new login. Then close the entire private window.
+
+Pass: Keycloak logout invalidates the active Synapse session. Fail: Element can
+continue syncing after logout, the logout endpoint reports an error, or a new
+login enters without authentication after the private window is closed.
+
+## Primary references
+
+Validated on 2026-07-15 against:
+
+- [Keycloak: Managing OpenID Connect clients](https://www.keycloak.org/docs/latest/server_admin/#_oidc_clients)
+- [Keycloak: OIDC authentication flows](https://www.keycloak.org/docs/latest/server_admin/#con-oidc-auth-flows_server_administration_guide)
+- [Synapse: Keycloak OIDC configuration](https://element-hq.github.io/synapse/latest/openid.html#keycloak)
+- [Synapse: OIDC provider settings](https://element-hq.github.io/synapse/latest/usage/configuration/config_documentation.html#oidc_providers)
+
+The Synapse documentation defines the callback as
+`[public_baseurl]/_synapse/client/oidc/callback`, documents Keycloak's
+confidential client and back-channel logout support, and supports
+`client_secret_path` so the runtime credential need not appear in versioned
+configuration.
