@@ -0,0 +1,369 @@
+# Matrix Operations, Emergency And Rollback Runbook
+
+**Parent:** Matrix Server Epic #212
+
+**Operational scope:** Synapse, PostgreSQL, Coturn and the Matrix adapter
+
+**Release contract:** #241, `docs/releases/matrix-profile-v1.md`
+
+This runbook is the operator entry point for normal operation, upgrades,
+rollback and emergencies. It deliberately contains placeholders rather than
+credentials. Replace every `<...>` value locally before running a command and
+never commit the substituted command or its output when it contains a secret.
+
+Telegram and Signal remain independent external fallback channels throughout
+all Matrix operations. No step in this runbook disables either channel.
+
+## Preconditions And Release Evidence
+
+Run commands from a clean checkout of the Architecture repository on the Pi 5.
+Record command output in the change ticket, excluding environment variables,
+secret paths and secret contents.
+
+Set and validate the non-secret identifiers first:
+
+```bash
+export RELEASE_COMMIT='<release-commit>'
+export PREVIOUS_RELEASE_COMMIT='<previous-release-commit>'
+export BACKUP_TIMESTAMP='<backup-timestamp>'
+export ROTATION_ID='<rotation-id>'
+
+test "$RELEASE_COMMIT" != '<release-commit>'
+test "$PREVIOUS_RELEASE_COMMIT" != '<previous-release-commit>'
+test "$BACKUP_TIMESTAMP" != '<backup-timestamp>'
+test "$ROTATION_ID" != '<rotation-id>'
+```
+
+Before a release-changing action, require all of the following evidence:
+
+1. The `homelab-release/v1` manifest passes the offline validator from #185.
+2. `docs/releases/matrix-profile-v1.md` exists and names the exact Synapse
+   digest, adapter version, config checksum and PostgreSQL compatibility.
+3. The release profile records a successful backup, restore evidence and smoke
+   test evidence for this release.
+4. The release commit is present locally and its tree is clean.
+5. The secret files required by both Compose files exist and are non-empty.
+6. The previous known-good release commit and its compatibility classification
+   are recorded before the change starts.
+
+Fail closed if the release profile does not exist yet:
+
+```bash
+test -f docs/releases/matrix-profile-v1.md
+git cat-file -e "$RELEASE_COMMIT^{commit}"
+git cat-file -e "$PREVIOUS_RELEASE_COMMIT^{commit}"
+test -z "$(git status --porcelain)"
+```
+
+Validate Compose without printing interpolated configuration. Plain
+`docker compose config` output can expose secret file paths, so redirect it:
+
+```bash
+docker compose -f pi/compose/synapse.yml config --quiet
+docker compose -f pi/compose/coturn.yml config --quiet
+```
+
+The existing `pi/backupMatrix.sh` and `pi/restoreMatrix.md` implement the #235
+PoC artifact contract under `/mnt/hardDrive/docker/synapse-poc`. They are not a
+production backup for `pi/compose/synapse.yml`, whose volumes live under
+`/mnt/hardDrive/docker/synapse`. Do not run them against production until the
+release profile explicitly maps and validates the production restore inputs.
+This mismatch is an upgrade and restore stop condition, not a warning to waive.
+
+## Start And Stop
+
+### Start
+
+Start the externally reachable TURN service first, then the database and
+Synapse. The adapter starts only after Synapse health succeeds.
+
+```bash
+git switch --detach "$RELEASE_COMMIT"
+docker compose -f pi/compose/coturn.yml config --quiet
+docker compose -f pi/compose/synapse.yml config --quiet
+docker compose -f pi/compose/coturn.yml up -d
+docker compose -f pi/compose/synapse.yml up -d
+docker compose -f pi/compose/coturn.yml ps
+docker compose -f pi/compose/synapse.yml ps
+```
+
+Use the host processor's documented service command to start or restart the
+adapter only after completing Health Verification. Do not improvise a second
+adapter process.
+
+### Stop
+
+Stop the adapter first so its sync token reaches stable storage. Then stop
+Synapse and Coturn. Keep PostgreSQL running during brief maintenance; use
+`down` only for a full stack shutdown.
+
+```bash
+docker compose -f pi/compose/synapse.yml stop synapse
+docker compose -f pi/compose/coturn.yml stop coturn
+```
+
+For a full shutdown after the adapter is stopped:
+
+```bash
+docker compose -f pi/compose/synapse.yml down
+docker compose -f pi/compose/coturn.yml down
+```
+
+## Health Verification
+
+All checks are mandatory. A healthy container alone is not sufficient.
+
+```bash
+docker compose -f pi/compose/synapse.yml ps
+docker compose -f pi/compose/coturn.yml ps
+curl --fail --silent --show-error \
+  https://matrix.hl.maier.wtf/_matrix/client/versions >/dev/null
+curl --fail --silent --show-error \
+  https://matrix.hl.maier.wtf/health >/dev/null
+docker compose -f pi/compose/synapse.yml exec -T postgres \
+  pg_isready -U synapse -d synapse
+```
+
+Also verify through the adapter's normal status interface:
+
+1. Matrix polling is current and has no repeated authentication failures.
+2. A synthetic inbound Matrix message reaches the expected local route.
+3. A synthetic outbound reply reaches the same Matrix room exactly once.
+4. Telegram and Signal status checks remain healthy.
+5. No secret value appears in container or processor logs.
+
+Abort when any check fails. Capture redacted logs with
+`docker compose ... logs --since <timestamp>` and choose Rollback or Emergency
+Isolation according to the release profile's rollback classification.
+
+## Upgrade
+
+Never upgrade from a floating branch. The exact release commit must contain the
+immutable image digests and checksums accepted by #241.
+
+1. Complete Preconditions And Release Evidence.
+2. Stop the adapter and record its final sync position without recording tokens.
+3. Verify the production backup identified by `$BACKUP_TIMESTAMP` against its
+   checksum manifest.
+4. Switch to the exact release commit.
+5. Validate both Compose files, start Coturn and Synapse, then run all health
+   and message-flow checks.
+6. Start the adapter only after Synapse is healthy.
+7. Keep the previous checkout, backup and fallback channels available until
+   the observation window in the release profile has passed.
+
+```bash
+export BACKUP_DIR="/mnt/hardDrive/backups/synapse/$BACKUP_TIMESTAMP"
+test -d "$BACKUP_DIR"
+(cd "$BACKUP_DIR" && sha256sum -c sha256sums.txt)
+git switch --detach <release-commit>
+git switch --detach "$RELEASE_COMMIT"
+docker compose -f pi/compose/coturn.yml config --quiet
+docker compose -f pi/compose/synapse.yml config --quiet
+docker compose -f pi/compose/coturn.yml up -d
+docker compose -f pi/compose/synapse.yml up -d
+```
+
+The literal `git switch --detach <release-commit>` above documents the required
+placeholder. Execute only the quoted variable form after validation.
+
+## Rollback
+
+Read the release profile before changing containers or data:
+
+- `config-only` or `application-compatible`: return to the previous immutable
+  release and run Health Verification.
+- `database-migration-compatible`: use only the downgrade sequence explicitly
+  recorded in the release profile.
+- `restore-required`: never start the old Synapse against the changed database;
+  use Restore with the pre-upgrade backup.
+
+Compatible rollback sequence:
+
+```bash
+docker compose -f pi/compose/synapse.yml stop synapse
+docker compose -f pi/compose/coturn.yml stop coturn
+git switch --detach <previous-release-commit>
+git switch --detach "$PREVIOUS_RELEASE_COMMIT"
+docker compose -f pi/compose/coturn.yml config --quiet
+docker compose -f pi/compose/synapse.yml config --quiet
+docker compose -f pi/compose/coturn.yml up -d
+docker compose -f pi/compose/synapse.yml up -d
+```
+
+The literal placeholder command is documentation only. Execute the validated
+variable form. Restart the adapter and complete Health Verification only after
+Synapse is healthy. Preserve failed-release logs and evidence, but never secret
+values.
+
+## Restore
+
+Restore is destructive and operator-approved. Use it only for a
+`restore-required` rollback or verified data loss.
+
+1. Stop the adapter, Synapse and Coturn.
+2. Verify the selected backup with `sha256sum -c sha256sums.txt`.
+3. Confirm the backup contains the production database dump, media, original
+   signing key and adapter state required by the release profile.
+4. Follow `pi/restoreMatrix.md` only when its paths match the release profile.
+   It currently describes the PoC paths and therefore cannot authorize a
+   production restore by itself.
+5. Restore into isolated replacement paths first. Do not overwrite the active
+   database or signing key until checksum and ownership checks pass.
+6. Start PostgreSQL, then Synapse, then Coturn, and finally the adapter.
+7. Complete Health Verification and record restore evidence.
+
+```bash
+export BACKUP_DIR="/mnt/hardDrive/backups/synapse/$BACKUP_TIMESTAMP"
+test -d "$BACKUP_DIR"
+(cd "$BACKUP_DIR" && sha256sum -c sha256sums.txt)
+```
+
+If production path mapping is absent from `docs/releases/matrix-profile-v1.md`,
+stop. Do not translate the PoC paths by intuition.
+
+## Credential Rotation
+
+Every rotation needs an approved `$ROTATION_ID`, a rollback value retained in
+the credential store for the bounded validation window, and redacted evidence.
+Never print, diff or pass a credential on the command line.
+
+### TURN shared secret
+
+1. Generate the replacement directly in the credential store.
+2. Update the Coturn and Synapse secret files as one coordinated change.
+3. Restart Coturn and Synapse, then test a real relay allocation.
+4. Roll both files back together if either service or media relay fails.
+
+### Matrix adapter access token
+
+1. Create a replacement token for the existing least-privilege service user.
+2. Stop the adapter, replace the credential through its credential-store
+   mechanism, and restart it.
+3. Verify inbound and outbound flow before revoking the previous token.
+4. Revoke the previous token after the bounded validation window.
+
+### PostgreSQL password
+
+Coordinate the database role password and the Compose secret file. Stop
+Synapse during the change and verify `pg_isready` plus a Synapse health check
+before ending the maintenance window.
+
+### Synapse signing key
+
+The signing key is server identity, not a routine credential. Preserve it in
+backups and restores. Rotate it only under a separately reviewed identity-key
+procedure that documents federation and signature consequences, even while
+federation remains disabled.
+
+## Emergency Isolation
+
+Use isolation for credential exposure, uncontrolled message duplication,
+suspected database corruption or unexpected public reachability.
+
+```bash
+docker compose -f pi/compose/synapse.yml stop synapse
+docker compose -f pi/compose/coturn.yml stop coturn
+```
+
+Then stop the Matrix adapter through its normal service control, preserve
+redacted logs, and verify that the public Matrix health endpoint no longer
+responds successfully. Do not delete containers, volumes, networks, backups or
+credentials during evidence collection. PostgreSQL may remain running on its
+internal network unless database compromise is suspected.
+
+Recovery requires an identified cause, an accepted release or credential
+rotation, and the complete Health Verification sequence.
+
+## External Fallback
+
+Telegram and Signal are the continuity path when Matrix is unavailable.
+
+1. Keep both polling transports enabled before, during and after Matrix work.
+2. Confirm `/status` through Telegram and Signal before starting maintenance.
+3. Announce the Matrix-only outage through both external channels without
+   including internal hostnames, tokens or diagnostic payloads.
+4. Process urgent commands through their existing routes; do not create a new
+   emergency bot or polling process.
+5. Confirm both external channels again after Matrix recovery.
+
+A Matrix outage must not trigger changes to Telegram or Signal credentials,
+offset files or routing policy.
+
+## Operator Blackbox Test
+
+This test is performed by an authorized operator in a maintenance window. It
+does not require implementation knowledge, but it does require an accepted
+release profile and a production-compatible backup contract.
+
+### 1. Validate release inputs
+
+**Action:** Set the four non-secret variables from the approved change ticket,
+run Preconditions And Release Evidence, and validate both Compose files.
+
+**Expected:** Every `test`, `git cat-file` and `config --quiet` exits zero.
+
+**Evidence:** Record release commit, previous commit, profile version and exit
+codes.
+
+**Abort:** Any unresolved placeholder, dirty tree, missing profile or non-zero
+exit stops the test before runtime changes.
+
+### 2. Verify fallback
+
+**Action:** Request `/status` once through Telegram and once through Signal.
+
+**Expected:** Both requests return their normal status response.
+
+**Evidence:** Record timestamps and message identifiers, not message contents.
+
+**Abort:** Do not change Matrix while either fallback channel is unhealthy.
+
+### 3. Verify backup
+
+**Action:** Select `<backup-timestamp>` from the ticket and run the checksum
+command in Restore. Confirm the profile maps every artifact to production.
+
+**Expected:** `sha256sum` exits zero and all required artifact classes exist.
+
+**Evidence:** Record backup identifier, checksum-manifest hash and result.
+
+**Abort:** Missing, PoC-only or invalid backup evidence stops the test.
+
+### 4. Controlled restart
+
+**Action:** Stop the adapter through normal service control, run Stop, run
+Start, and then run Health Verification. Restart the adapter last.
+
+**Expected:** Both Compose projects report healthy services; public client and
+health endpoints, PostgreSQL and adapter status all pass.
+
+**Evidence:** Record container image digests, health exit codes and timestamps.
+
+**Abort:** Isolate the failed Matrix component and execute Rollback. Keep
+Telegram and Signal active.
+
+### 5. End-to-end message flow
+
+**Action:** Send one uniquely identified synthetic Matrix message and one reply
+through the approved test room. Recheck Telegram and Signal `/status`.
+
+**Expected:** Exactly one inbound event and one outbound reply are observed;
+both fallback checks still pass.
+
+**Evidence:** Record redacted event identifiers, timestamps and route result.
+
+**Abort:** Duplicate, missing or misrouted events trigger Emergency Isolation.
+
+### 6. Declare result
+
+**Action:** Compare all evidence with the accepted release profile and change
+ticket.
+
+**Expected:** Steps 1 through 5 pass without a waived criterion.
+
+**Evidence:** Record `PASS`, the release commit and operator identity in the
+ticket.
+
+**Abort:** Any unmet criterion is `FAIL`; restore the previous known-good state
+or leave Matrix isolated. Never mark a partial run as successful.
