@@ -0,0 +1,126 @@
+# Matrix Security Hardening And Retention
+
+This baseline applies to the private Synapse deployment defined in
+`pi/compose/synapse.yml`. It is a release gate, not permission to deploy. The
+deployment remains private, client-only, and non-federated until a separate ADR
+and operator approval change that boundary.
+
+## Registration And Identity
+
+- `enable_registration` and `enable_registration_without_verification` remain
+  `false`; CI rejects either value becoming true.
+- Human operator login uses the reviewed Keycloak OIDC client. Lydia, Slarti,
+  gateways, and Veklinge use separate non-admin service identities.
+- Service tokens are scoped to one identity and stored outside Git. They are
+  never shared with the Synapse server-admin or break-glass account.
+- The break-glass account is pre-provisioned, disabled for routine use, and
+  recovered through the operator-controlled credential store.
+- Room power levels are applied from `runtime/matrix/room_policy.json`; Veklinge
+  and gateways receive no global or room administration rights.
+
+## TLS And Network Boundary
+
+- Public client traffic terminates at the existing frontproxy on HTTPS 443.
+  Synapse exposes port 8008 only to Docker networks and publishes no host port.
+- PostgreSQL joins only `synapse_internal`, which is marked `internal: true`.
+  It never joins frontproxy and never publishes port 5432.
+- The only Synapse listener resource is `client`. Federation listeners, port
+  8448, and `/.well-known/matrix/server` are absent in private mode.
+- Synapse trusts forwarded headers only from the Docker proxy path. Direct
+  public access to container ports is prohibited.
+- TLS hostname and certificate verification are release smoke tests. An invalid
+  certificate blocks promotion; it does not trigger an insecure HTTP fallback.
+
+## Resource And Abuse Limits
+
+- Synapse is limited to 1.5 GiB RAM and 2 CPUs; PostgreSQL is limited to 512 MiB
+  RAM and 1 CPU. A release must remeasure idle and active use on the Pi 5.
+- The adapter rejects attachments above its configured size before downstream
+  processing and validates MIME type and SHA-256 after download.
+- Login, message, media, and room-creation rate limits use Synapse defaults until
+  measured private-room traffic justifies a stricter versioned override. Any
+  override must be tested against `/status`, attachment, and reconnect flows.
+- Disk alarms apply at 80 percent used or less than 20 GiB free; 90 percent or
+  less than 10 GiB free is critical and stops nonessential ingestion.
+- Docker logs are bounded to seven 10 MiB files per Matrix container.
+
+## Retention And Privacy
+
+- Agent-room events are retained for 90 days during the controlled rollout.
+  A shorter room-specific policy may be applied for sensitive document rooms.
+- Media is removed when its owning event expires and after a successful backup.
+  Cached remote media remains irrelevant while federation is disabled.
+- Audit records retain event IDs, trace IDs, fixed reason codes, timestamps, and
+  counters for 30 days. They do not retain message bodies or attachment bytes.
+- Backup generations follow `docs/matrix/storage-and-retention.md`: current plus
+  two predecessors. Expired backup material is securely removed by the existing
+  backup rotation mechanism.
+- Matrix transports commands and responses. Gitea and Lydia remain authoritative
+  for task state, so Matrix retention cannot delete the authoritative task.
+
+Retention enforcement is an operator acceptance item in the seven-day parallel
+run. If Synapse cannot enforce the selected event/media policy reproducibly,
+Matrix must not become the primary internal channel.
+
+## Logging And Redaction
+
+- Synapse, adapter, and proxy logs must not include access tokens, Authorization
+  headers, OIDC secrets, database passwords, message bodies, or binary payloads.
+- Adapter logs use event ID, room ID, trace ID, fixed outcome, and exception
+  class. Unknown free-text errors are not copied into structured audit records.
+- Quarantined attachments log a fixed reason code and event ID only. Downloads
+  remain untrusted and are never executed.
+- Debug logging is disabled in production. Temporary diagnostic logging needs a
+  time limit, operator approval, and a post-incident deletion step.
+
+## Backup And Incident Response
+
+- A release requires a PostgreSQL dump, media archive, signing key, adapter
+  cursor/deduplication state, configuration checksum, and restore evidence as
+  defined by `docs/matrix/backup-and-restore.md`.
+- Signing keys, database credentials, OIDC secrets, and access tokens are
+  external files under `/home/michael/matrix/secrets/` with restrictive host
+  permissions. CI rejects repository or `/tmp` secret paths.
+- A database-incompatible downgrade always restores the matching backup. It is
+  never attempted against a newer live database.
+- On suspected credential exposure: isolate the affected adapter, preserve
+  redacted evidence, keep Telegram/Signal available, rotate only the affected
+  credential with operator approval, and verify no replay before re-enabling.
+- On suspected server compromise: remove Synapse from frontproxy, stop Matrix
+  adapters, preserve volumes, alert through an external gateway, and follow the
+  restore runbook. Do not delete evidence or persistent volumes during triage.
+
+## Agent Rooms And E2EE
+
+Automated agent rooms do not enable end-to-end encryption in the first release.
+The current bot path has no reviewed key backup, verification, rotation, and
+multi-device recovery contract. Enabling E2EE prematurely would make unattended
+messages unreadable or silently unrecoverable after state loss. TLS, private
+membership, restrictive power levels, dedicated identities, and host encryption
+boundaries protect the initial transport. E2EE requires a separate ADR and
+restore-tested bot implementation.
+
+## Threat-To-Control Matrix
+
+| Risk | Epic threat | Preventive controls | Detection and recovery |
+|---|---|---|---|
+| RISK-01 | Pi resource exhaustion | CPU/RAM limits, attachment limits, private rooms, bounded logs | Resource baseline, disk alarms, abort parallel run and stop Matrix only |
+| RISK-02 | Federation accidentally exposed | Client-only listener, no 8448, private discovery contract, no host ports | External federation probes must fail; remove Synapse from proxy on violation |
+| RISK-03 | Bots cannot process E2EE | E2EE disabled for agent rooms pending reviewed key lifecycle | Client-room check; fall back to unencrypted private room or Telegram/Signal |
+| RISK-04 | Bridges create loops | Envelope trace, origin, hop count, and durable deduplication | Audited loop reason; disable bridge path without stopping external gateways |
+| RISK-05 | Matrix treated as task queue | Gitea/Lydia remain authoritative; Matrix carries events only | Reconcile task IDs against authority and replay from authoritative state |
+| RISK-06 | Signing key or database loss | External secrets, automated backup, three generations | Mandatory restore test; restore matching key, DB, media, and adapter state |
+| RISK-07 | Selected homeserver becomes unmaintained | Digest-pinned Synapse release profile and explicit upgrade review | Maintenance review before release; export and restore test before migration |
+
+## Verification
+
+Run the static policy and the complete Architecture CI suite from the repository
+root:
+
+```bash
+bash pi/tests/test_matrix_hardening.sh
+make ci
+```
+
+The static test also mutates safe inputs and proves that open registration,
+floating images, PostgreSQL host ports, and insecure secret paths are rejected.
